/trending

Based upon user's activity :
- read points = 3
- share points = 10
- comment points = 5
- like points = 2
- Dislike points = -5



last 5 min rank score = total_points * 1 * and associated cumulative points sum percentile
last 1 hour rank score = total_points * 0.8 * and associated cumulative points sum percentile
last 6 hour rank score = total_points * 0.6 * and associated cumulative points sum percentile
last 12 hour rank score = total_points * 0.4 * and associated cumulative points sum percentile
last 24 hour rank score = total_points * 0.2 * and associated cumulative points sum percentile

Use this for trending

Calculation for /trending in real world

1 billion interactions in a day (10 million & 100 times)
parallely aggregate them into location bounding boxes

If we calculate in a day

each activity = {time, article_id, user_id, activity_type, loc, loc_boundingbox}

lets suppose we have 1000000 bounding boxes for whole world

map each activity to the bounding_box via map_reduce

Seems like O(n+m) every time, where n is number of bounding boxes and m is number of activities. Can't go through billion rows sequentially, needs map reduce

each maching handling 1000000 activities (20 cores of each machine, via multithreading and storing partial result in local SSDs + SQL), mostly one bounding box by one machine chosen via consistent hashing, total 10 machines, returning into populating each boundingbox_articleId mappings in around 10-20 minutes, 




